            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0030">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec1.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>1.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Rationale: environmental impacts of mulch use in apple production</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">Agriculture is responsible for 10–12% of total direct global anthropogenic GHG emissions (i.e. at the field level) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0045" refid="bib31">Yue et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), and 19–29% when taking into account the entire food system (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0050" refid="bib27">Vermeulen et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>). This includes 84% of anthropogenic emissions of nitrous oxide (N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0055" refid="bib25">Smith et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>), a greenhouse gas with a global warming potential 298 times that of CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0060" refid="bib12">IPCC, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Agricultural soils are also an important potential carbon sink, meaning that they have the potential to remove carbon from the atmosphere and store it, thus inhibiting its ability to contribute to global warming via the greenhouse effect. Launched at the COP21 meeting in Paris in 2015, the “4 per 1000” initiative aims to increase global agricultural soil organic carbon (SOC) stocks by 0.4% annually, which would effectively halt current increases in atmospheric CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> levels (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0065" refid="bib22">4p1000 2017</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Mulch has been used in agriculture to increase yield and to improve a variety of soil properties (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0070" refid="bib20">Neilsen et al., 2003a</ce:cross-ref>). High C:N ratio mulches, such as shredded paper or wood, have been shown to improve water retention by improving the water-holding capacity of the soil and reducing evaporation from the surface (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0075" refid="bib20">Neilsen et al., 2003a</ce:cross-ref>). Mulch has also been shown to reduce weeds (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0080" refid="bib20">Neilsen et al., 2003a</ce:cross-ref>) and other parasites like root-lesion nematodes (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0085" refid="bib5">Forge et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). It is also a source of nutrients which can increase soil fertility (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0090" refid="bib20">Neilsen et al., 2003a</ce:cross-ref>). Due to these and other benefits of mulch, the addition of wood-based mulch can increase the yield and vigor of crops (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0095" refid="bib21">Neilsen et al., 2003b</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">In addition to these benefits of mulch application, recent work by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0100" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> has shown that, without affecting yield, using wood chip and bark mulch (referred to hereafter as mulch, or bark mulch) as a soil amendment on an apple orchard in the semi-arid Okanagan Valley region of western Canada reduced direct N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions by 19%. The salt-extractable SOC content of the mulched plots was also 68% higher than the non-mulched plots in the year after mulch application. Although this represents a potentially significant reduction in GHG emissions at the orchard scale, additional research is required prior to recommendation of bark mulch use for climate-friendly agriculture. This is because other processes related to the life cycle of bark mulch, including its production, transportation and management activities, may result in GHG emissions and other environmental impacts that offset these benefits (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0105" refid="bib14">Jäppinen et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). As well, the addition of bark mulch may affect other environmentally significant emissions, such as CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>. These trade-offs can be assessed using life cycle assessment.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec1.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>1.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Life cycle assessment</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">Life cycle assessment (LCA) is a systems-level sustainability decision support tool that can be used to assess the environmental impact of a product throughout its entire life cycle (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0110" refid="bib8">Guinee et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). The goal of LCA is to characterize all of the environmental inputs and outputs that occur as a result of activities linked to the life cycle of the product being studied, to use these values to perform an environmental impact assessment, and to subsequently support conclusions and recommendations about the use of the product. It is widely applicable to such purposes as hot-spot identification (identifying the areas within a life cycle with the largest environmental impacts), product improvement or creation, and supporting comparative assertions between different product alternatives (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0115" refid="bib8">Guinee et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>). Attributional LCA (ALCA) examines a snapshot of the current or past state of affairs to determine the environmental impacts that can be attributed to the product studied (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0120" refid="bib30">Weidema, 2003</ce:cross-ref>). Attributional LCA can be used to determine the impacts of the production of the product as it currently is produced, which is the focus of Part 1 of this research (this paper). Consequential LCA can expand the system to include the life cycle of displaced alternative technologies due to a change in use of the product studied, and is used in Part 2 (Bamber et al. unpublished).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">The goal of this research was to determine the net environmental impacts attributable to the current use of bark mulch as a soil amendment on Okanagan Valley apple orchard, from cradle to orchard gate, per unit of fruit produced. By performing an ALCA of this system, it can be determined whether there is a net increase or decrease in GHG and other emissions and resource use with mulch application, when the entire life cycle of the mulch is included in the analysis. This provides novel information regarding mulch use that can be used by orchardists and policy-makers to improve horticultural sustainability.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">To determine the net environmental impacts of apple production both with and without wood and bark chip mulch as a soil amendment, an ISO compliant (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0125" refid="bib13">ISO, 2006</ce:cross-ref>) ALCA was performed. The entire cradle-to-orchard gate life cycle of Okanagan apple production was examined, from the extraction of the resources necessary for the production of all orchard inputs, to the production of the apples. Impacts were assessed in terms of the production of 1 kg of apples. The data used comprised a combination of field-level site-specific data and information from published literature, models and databases that were adapted as appropriate to best approximate regional conditions. The details of the ALCA methods, which correspond to the requirements of the international reference standard for life cycle assessment, ISO 14044 (2006), are as follows (Sections <ce:cross-refs id="crosrefs0010" refid="sec1 sec2">2.1-2.4</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0050">Goal and scope</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.1" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0055">Goals</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">The primary goal of the ALCA was to determine and compare the net environmental impacts of apple production in the Okanagan with and without the use of bark mulch as a soil amendment. A secondary goal was to determine the relative impacts of the mulch compared to all of the other orchard inputs, and to determine the most important contributors to the environmental impacts of apple production.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.2" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0060">Intended audience</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">The intended audience included agricultural policy makers, orchard owners, and academics. Some of the key stakeholders were the orchard managers and the suppliers of the mulch. This LCA was not used to make comparative assertions (defined by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0130" refid="bib13">ISO (2006)</ce:cross-ref> as an environmental claim asserting superiority of one product over a competing product) because it considered the addition of a soil amendment to an orchard, which would otherwise not have the amendment added, producing the same product in either case: apples.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.3" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0065">System boundaries</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">The overall scope of this ALCA was cradle-to-orchard gate, meaning it included all stages from the extraction of raw materials, to the production of the apples on an orchard in the Okanagan Valley, but not the consumption and end-of-life stages. This included the production and application of mulch and all other inputs to the orchard, as well as all associated resource use and emissions (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0135" refid="fig1">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>). However it should be noted that, due to the study design, the irrigation and pesticide inputs were identical across all treatments. The temporal and geographical bounds included the most recent available data for the Okanagan Valley for background systems that feed into orchard inputs, with all site-specific data sourced from within the last 7 years from Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada’s Summerland Research and Development Centre (SuRDC) located near Summerland, British Columbia. The technological boundary included the average technology present in orchards in the Okanagan, as this boundary will suffice for most LCAs (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0140" refid="bib8">Guinee et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.1.4" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.1.4</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0070">Co-product allocation</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">In the case of any multi-functionality problems (i.e. when a process produces more than one product) in upstream datasets, co-products were allocated environmental burdens based on relative gross energy content or mass.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0075">Life cycle inventory</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.2.1" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.2.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0080">Flow diagram and system boundaries</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">All data necessary to model the orchard system were represented in a flow diagram (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0145" refid="fig1">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). This flow diagram distinguishes between the foreground processes (those processes specific to the product system being studied, for which more precise data are needed) and the background processes (the upstream processes linked to the foreground processes that are inputs to many product systems, for which more generic data can be used). Foreground processes for this system are those occurring directly on the orchard, including fertilizer, irrigation, mulch, and pesticide application types and amounts, as well as experimentally measured orchard-level emissions of N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O and CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>. Details regarding the orchard-level foreground data collection process were documented in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0150" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref>, along with all relevant technological, geographical, temporal and climatic data. Orchard-level emissions (other than N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O) from fertilizer, herbicides and pesticides were modelled using <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0155" refid="bib11">IPCC (2006)</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0160" refid="bib2">Dalgaard et al. (2008)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0165" refid="bib16">Margni et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref> methods, respectively, and are described in detail in sections <ce:cross-refs id="crosrefs0015" refid="sec2.2.2.1 sec2.2.2.3">2.2.2.1 and 2.2.2.3</ce:cross-refs>. Soil carbon (C) sequestration from added biomass (mulch) was estimated based on the methods in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0170" refid="bib23">Petersen et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref>, described in detail in section <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0175" refid="sec2.2.2.4">2.2.2.4</ce:cross-ref>. The background processes are those that fed into these orchard processes, such as the production of the fertilizer, plant protection products, etc., and all related processes, resource use and emissions. Data for background processes were taken from life cycle inventory (LCI) databases, including ecoinvent v.3.4 Allocation at the point of substitution (APOS) and Agri-footprint v.3.0 (available for download at <ce:inter-ref id="intref0010" xlink:href="https://nexus.openlca.org/databases" xlink:type="simple">https://nexus.openlca.org/databases</ce:inter-ref>). These data sets were altered as appropriate to be better representative of the region (described in detail below).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec2.2.2" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.2.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0085">Model</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">The apple orchard system was modelled in OpenLCA 1.7.4, an open-source LCA modelling software created by Green Delta (available at <ce:inter-ref id="intref0015" xlink:href="http://www.openlca.org/download/" xlink:type="simple">http://www.openlca.org/download/</ce:inter-ref>). The main process modelled was “Apple production on orchard”, with an output of 1 kg of apples. This apple production process was duplicated to compare the orchard plots that had bark mulch applied to the soil (mulch), and those that had no soil amendments (clean). These processes were duplicated again to compare the two different nitrogen fertilizer treatments in the experimental set-up: high nitrogen (40 g per tree) and low nitrogen (20 g per tree). Apple yield and the inputs to each apple production process were the same, except for an additional input of mulch on the mulch systems, and the differing amounts of nitrogen application. The measured emissions also differed between the four processes.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">Processes involved in orchard setup and teardown were not included in the model for several reasons. First, the orchard setup and teardown stages have been shown to have only a small impact compared to other life cycle stages (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0180" refid="bib24">Sanderson et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Second, the goal of this study, as outlined above, was to determine the impact of mulch use on the orchard, so the setup and teardown of the orchard were not considered relevant to the studied product system.</ce:para>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.1" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.1</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0090">Fertilizer application</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">Fertilizer input types and amounts were derived from SuRDC fertilizer application logs. All fertilizer product flows were modelled using LCIs from the ecoinvent v.3.4 Allocation at the Point Of Substitution (APOS) model database. SuRDC gave target amounts of nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), potassium (K) and boron (B) applied per tree per year, and these numbers were scaled to the functional unit. The specific LCI models for nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium and boron fertilizers were chosen to best represent the forms of these fertilizers indicated by SuRDC (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0185" refid="appsec1">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). Fertilizer was applied via fertigation, so any necessary equipment or machinery was included in the irrigation model. The ecoinvent background processes were modified, wherever possible, to best represent production in the appropriate area (for these and all other background processes mentioned) (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0190" refid="appsec1">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                           <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">The modelling of transportation of fertilizer by truck from the sites of production to the orchard was based on the Okanagan cherry orchard LCA by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0195" refid="bib24">Sanderson et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref>. Nitrogen fertilizer came from Carseland, Alberta (666 km). Phosphate rock sourced from northern Ontario (2887 km) was used as phosphorus fertilizer. Potassium fertilizer came from Saskatchewan (1315 km), and Solubor (boron fertilizer) from Boron, California (2096 km). Emissions of ammonia (NH<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>), nitrate (NO<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>), nitrogen oxides (NOx), and phosphorous (P) from fertilizer were estimated using the <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0200" refid="bib11">IPCC (2006)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0205" refid="bib2">Dalgaard et al. (2008)</ce:cross-ref> models (ESM – <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0210" refid="appsec1">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions were not calculated here since site-specific N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions were measured and provided from the SuRDC experiments.</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.2" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.2</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0095">Irrigation</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">
                              <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0215" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> described two different irrigation frequency treatments: every day (high) or every second day (low). The values used in this model were taken from the high frequency treatments, although the total amount is the same between the two treatments and this model only accounts for total amount, not frequency. The average monthly water usage was given by SuRDC and scaled to the functional unit, then modelled using the “irrigation” process from ecoinvent v.3.4 APOS, which contains LCI flows for both the irrigation water, and the process of application (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0220" refid="appsec1">Table S2</ce:cross-ref>). The process is representative of irrigation in Quebec, which was chosen as the most geographically representative process, and modified to include lake water as the source of water.</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.3" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.3</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0100">Plant protection</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">Total amounts of plant protection products, including herbicides, fungicides, and insecticides applied from 2013 to 2014 were supplied by SuRDC (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0225" refid="appsec1">Table S3</ce:cross-ref>). Plant protection products for which there was an exact match in the databases used were modelled accordingly. Those products include 2,4-D, carbaryl, paraquat, pendimethalin and glyphosate. All others were modelled by the most representative process available, i.e. the inventories from LCI datasets that are representative of either a similar chemical, or a generic set of chemicals such as herbicides. Transportation by truck of plant protection products was included, based on the distance from the Alberta location of Bayer CropScience, a leading supplier of plant protection products for Western Canada (609 km). All transport modelled included only the distance to transport the product, not an empty return distance. Orchard-level emissions from plant protection product application were modelled based on the guidelines in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0230" refid="bib16">Margni et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref>, as implemented in the Okanagan cherry industry LCA by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0235" refid="bib24">Sanderson et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref>, assuming that 76.5% of the active ingredient of each agricultural plant protection product is emitted to soil, 8.5% to water, and 10% to air. The last 5% is taken up by the plant and was therefore not considered as an emission in this model.</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.4" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.4</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0105">Mulch</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">Wood chip and bark mulch application was modelled based on the “Mulch” soil amendment treatment in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0240" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref>. SuRDC reported that the mulch applied was mostly bark and partly wood chips. This was hence assumed to be 80% bark and 20% wood chips. In order to model wood chip and bark mulch production as co-products of lumber production at sawmills, alterations were made to the ecoinvent v.3.4 APOS processes for these flows in order to allocate, based on mass, the proportionate amount of emissions and resource use to both the lumber and the mulch (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0245" refid="appsec1">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>). For bark mulch, the process “bark chips production, softwood, at sawmill | bark chips, wet, measured as dry mass | APOS, U” was used, and altered to reflect the physical relationship between the mass of lumber produced and the mass of bark chips produced (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0250" refid="bib19">Natural Resources Canada and Forest Products Association of Canada, 2004</ce:cross-ref>). Similarly, the process “wood chips production, softwood, at sawmill | wood chips, wet, measured as dry mass | APOS, U″ was modified to reflect the mass ratio between lumber production and wood chip production. The ecoinvent v.3.4 APOS processes used were modified by removing the inputs related to the setup of the sawmill, since these processes are outside the scope of the study. The transport of the mulch to the orchard was modelled using the generic Agrifootprint v.3.0 truck transport flow LCI. The distance travelled was estimated as 50 km, an approximate average of different possible sources of mulch in the region (Tolko, Superior Peat, etc.). The ecoinvent process “mulching” was included to model the process of mulch application. The C added in the mulch was assumed to contribute to soil C sequestration. Since the land management practices were identical between the mulch and no mulch scenarios (due to the experimental design), the only difference in SOC came from the addition of C in mulch. To model this difference on a long-term basis, a percentage of 9.7% of C added to the orchard floor in the mulch was modelled as sequestered, as recommended in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0255" refid="bib23">Petersen et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref>, based on long-term experiments. This was modelled as an input of CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> as a resource from the air into the orchard model (ESM – <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0260" refid="appsec1">Table S4</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.5" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.5</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0110">Energy use</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0290" view="all">Based on the energy inputs reported in recent apple production LCA studies (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0265" refid="bib1">Annaert et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0270" refid="bib7">Goossens et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0275" refid="bib15">Longo et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0280" refid="bib29">Vinyes et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0285" refid="bib32">Zhu et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>), average inputs of 0.309 MJ diesel and 0.001638 kWh electricity per kg apple were estimated for on-orchard processes. In order to add this amount of energy use, but avoid double counting, direct energy inputs from the fertigation and plant protection application LCIs were subtracted from these amounts, and the remaining amounts of electricity and diesel use were added to the model (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0290" refid="appsec1">Table S5</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.6" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.6</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0115">Measured emissions</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">Field-level emissions to air of N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0295" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) and CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> (Fentabil and Nichol, unpublished data) for each treatment were modelled. All upstream emissions were embedded in the upstream processes in the LCI database processes used, or modelled as described above in the fertilizer and plant protection sections.</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                        <ce:section id="sec2.2.2.7" view="all">
                           <ce:label>2.2.2.7</ce:label>
                           <ce:section-title id="sectitle0120">Uncertainty</ce:section-title>
                           <ce:para id="p0300" view="all">Parameter uncertainty data were entered for all foreground processes in the model. When possible, a lognormal uncertainty distribution was calculated directly from the raw data (multiple replications of the same measurement for the same treatment). Where ranges of data were given, an uncertainty distribution was interpolated and represented as a lognormal distribution. This was used in combination with uncertainty related to data quality as estimated using a standard pedigree matrix. The pedigree matrix is a matrix of 5 different data quality indicators (DQIs) – reliability, completeness, temporal correlation, geographical correlation, further technological correlation – with five possible data quality scores, ranging from best quality (1) to worst (5). Each of these scores corresponds with a specific uncertainty value, depending on the specific pedigree matrix used, that is represented as the geometric standard deviation of a lognormal distribution (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0300" refid="bib6">Frischknecht et al., 2005</ce:cross-ref>). When the stochastic uncertainty distribution of the data was not known, the generic basic sectoral uncertainty factors from <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0305" refid="bib6">Frischknecht et al. (2005)</ce:cross-ref> were used, again in combination with the uncertainty from the pedigree matrix. These basic uncertainty factors are meant to represent the amount of inherent uncertainty for LCI data from the sector represented.</ce:para>
                        </ce:section>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0125">Impact assessment</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0305" view="all">The life cycle impact assessment (LCIA) phase includes the selection of impact categories and characterization models, the classification of LCI results into impact categories and the calculation of impact category indicator results (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0310" refid="bib13">ISO, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). As suggested by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0315" refid="bib8">Guinee et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref> for all LCAs, all the impact categories from the CML baseline LCIA methods were included in the assessment, as well as land use from CML non-baseline since this is an agricultural study. The cumulative energy demand was also included to assess the differences in (energy) resource use between the two scenarios. The impact assessment categories included were human toxicity, freshwater aquatic ecotoxicity, depletion of abiotic resources (elements, ultimate reserves), photochemical oxidation, ozone layer depletion, terrestrial ecotoxicity, acidification potential, climate change and eutrophication from the CML (baseline) [v4.4, January 2015] methods, land use – land competition from CML (non baseline) [v4.4, January 2015], and non-renewable resources – fossil, nuclear, and primary forest; and renewable resources – geothermal, solar, water, and wind from Cumulative Energy Demand [v1.0.1, January 2015]. These were chosen since they were the most commonly included impact categories in other apple LCA studies (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0320" refid="bib17">Milà I Canals et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0325" refid="bib18">Mouron et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0330" refid="bib28">Vinyes et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), and are in line with the categories suggested for inclusion by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0335" refid="bib8">Guinee et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref>. The Cumulative Energy Demand methods were chosen since they were the most comprehensive methods for assessing energy use available in openLCA. Similarly, CML (baseline and non-baseline) were chosen due to their availability for use in openLCA, and since they are slightly superior in terms of characterization of relevant elementary flows, compared to similar LCIA methods such as ReCiPe. In the CML (baseline) LCIA methods, the climate change impact category was altered to remove all characterization factors for biogenic CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> flows. This means that any biogenic CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>, defined by <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0340" refid="bib26">UC Davis (2019)</ce:cross-ref> as any CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> directly produced or taken up by living organisms in the short term, was not included in the impact assessment of the GHG emissions of any product’s life cycle. Importantly, this includes, among other sources, any carbon in the mulch or the apple trees. This was done because the purpose of LCA is to assess the resource use and emissions that occur due to the production of a product, in this case apples. Therefore, it is outside the scope of the assessment to include short-term C cycles that naturally occur in living organisms. It would be misleading to credit a product with the C taken out of the atmosphere by the growing of a tree, for example.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0310" view="all">The openLCA software platform was used for the classification and characterization steps of the LCIA, which consist of assigning LCI data to the aforementioned impact categories (including multiplication by the characterization factor) and calculating the aggregated results for each impact category. Uncertainty factors (geometric standard deviation) for the characterization models chosen were entered into the impact assessment methods in openLCA. These uncertainty factors were based on the generic uncertainty factors for impact categories presented in the supplementary information of <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0345" refid="bib10">Huijbregts et al. (2003)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0315" view="all">Finally, data quality analysis was performed to better understand the LCIA results (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0350" refid="bib13">ISO, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). This included gravity analysis, uncertainty analysis and sensitivity analysis. A gravity analysis was conducted to determine the processes or flows with the highest contribution to the impact category indicators. An uncertainty analysis was performed using Monte Carlo simulations (1000 runs) to determine the overall uncertainty of the impact assessment results based on both data uncertainty and characterization factor uncertainty (described above). An uncertainty contribution analysis was also performed to determine the relative amounts of uncertainty that come from foreground data variability, background data quality and impact assessment uncertainty. Due to software limitations, it was not possible to perform an uncertainty contribution analysis in one Monte Carlo simulation, therefore individual Monte Carlo’s were performed that accounted for each important source of uncertainty: parameter uncertainty, parameter plus impact assessment uncertainty, foreground data uncertainty, background data uncertainty, measured emissions uncertainty and mulch uncertainty. According to <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0355" refid="bib9">Henriksson et al. (2015)</ce:cross-ref>, when life cycle assessments are used to compare between multiple options, it is more important to compare the relative uncertainty of the options, rather than the absolute uncertainty of each. This is because there is a large amount of uncertainty in the background processes in LCA that are common to the compared processes, therefore only looking at relative uncertainty can help to better discern between processes. For this reason, a scenario was also created where only relative uncertainty was included in the uncertainty analysis. The results of these Monte Carlo simulations were used to determine the statistical significance of the differences between treatments using two factor analysis of variance (ANOVA). A sensitivity analysis was conducted to determine the influence of the C sequestration modelling on the results. Since soil C sequestration was estimated, the estimated percent of C sequestered (9.7%) was varied by 100% - i.e. ranging from half the value (4.85%) to double (19.4%).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.4" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0130">Interpretation</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0320" view="all">The life cycle interpretation phase included the evaluation of the completeness and consistency of the results (according to the goal and scope of the study) and the explanation of conclusions and recommendations, as well as limitations (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0360" refid="bib13">ISO, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). A completeness check was carried out to ensure all data were available and complete. A sensitivity check was performed to assess the sensitivity of results to uncertainty, data quality and methodological choices, and a consistency check was performed by reviewing all the previous LCA stages to assess the consistency of methods and assumptions with the goal and scope. Finally, conclusions and recommendations were made based on the impact assessment, completeness, sensitivity and consistency checks, and limitations of the study were identified.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0135">Results and discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0140">Impact assessment</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0325" view="all">Apples produced using mulch emitted around 25% more life cycle GHG emissions than those produced without mulch (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0365" refid="fig2">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>). All the GHG benefits of mulch at the orchard level were outweighed by GHG emissions arising from the mulch production, transportation, and application processes. These mulch production GHG emissions largely came from the electricity and fuel used for producing the wood and bark mulch (logging and sawmills) and from its transportation. Doubling the amount of nitrogen fertilizer increased the overall GHG emissions by around 20%. The modelled impacts from irrigation, plant protection and energy use were all the same in each treatment (since there were no significant differences in yield between the treatments). Only the impacts associated with mulch, fertilizer and orchard-level N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O and CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> emissions varied.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0330" view="all">Eutrophication is another impact category where the orchard-level emissions reductions associated with mulch were counteracted by the life cycle emissions from the mulch production and application stages, yielding around 15% higher eutrophication potential for the mulch treatments than for the clean treatments (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0370" refid="fig3">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig3"/>). The addition of mulch resulted in only slightly reduced N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emitted to the air. However, the production and application of the mulch resulted in higher emissions of PO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf>, NOx (0.13 kg PO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf> eq) and NO<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">−</ce:sup> (0.1 kg PO<ce:inf loc="post">4</ce:inf> eq) – largely from the production of electricity and the transportation of the mulch. In comparison, high nitrogen fertilizer application increased eutrophying emissions by 32%.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0335" view="all">For some impact categories, such as acidification potential, the addition of mulch resulted in increased life cycle impacts, which were not offset by any orchard-level effects (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0375" refid="fig4">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig4"/>). Mulch production and application resulted in SO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> and NOx (0.5 kg SO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> eq) emissions from electricity for bark mulch production, resulting in 23% higher acidification potential in the mulch treatments compared to clean. However, the main contributor to the acidification potential of apple production was fertilizer production, mainly due to NH<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> (1.6 kg SO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> eq) and nitrogen oxides emissions associated with nitric acid production for nitrogen fertilizer. High nitrogen fertilizer application increased acidifying emissions by 38%.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0340" view="all">Mulch production, transportation and application added an additional 33% to the life cycle human toxicity (kg 1,4-dichlorobenzene equivalent) emissions of apple production (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0380" refid="fig5">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig5"/>). This is due to toxic emissions such as selenium (5.6 kg 1,4-dichlorobenzene equivalent) and nickel (331 kg 1,4-dichlorobenzene equivalent) from the process of softwood transformation at the sawmill, and electricity use for this process. In comparison, high nitrogen fertilizer application increased human toxicity by 21%.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0345" view="all">In general, resource use was higher with mulch due to the resources required for the production and transformation of wood products, including wood chip and bark mulch as co-products. Land use was 139 times higher with mulch than without, due to the land needed to grow and produce the mulch (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0385" refid="fig6">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig6"/>), and the overall energy demand for apple production with mulch was 35 times higher than without mulch (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0390" refid="fig7">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig7"/>). There are many different sources of energy accounted for in the cumulative energy demand, most of which were fairly similar between treatments. The largest difference was due to the 766 times larger demand for biomass energy for the mulch – this was mostly the mulch biomass itself. The demand for other sources of renewable energy was lower overall but still almost double for mulched apple production, indicating the increased demand for these sources of energy in the production, transportation and application of the mulch. The total renewable energy demand of the mulched production systems was 470 times higher than non-mulched, and the non-renewable energy demand was 61% higher (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0395" refid="fig8">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig8"/>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0350" view="all">Overall, in all impact categories, apples produced using mulch had higher environmental impacts (generally ranging from 10% to 75% higher) than those produced without mulch. For land use and nuclear, biomass, water, wind and geothermal energy use, the impacts were orders of magnitude higher (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0400" refid="appsec1">Table S7</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0355" view="all">Fertilizer production, transportation and application was the highest contributor to 9 out of 19 impact categories, and second highest to 7 more (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0405" refid="tbl1">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl1"/>). The measured orchard-level emissions only impacted climate change (fourth highest contributor) and eutrophication (lowest contributor). The production, transportation and application of mulch was the highest contributor to 8 categories as well, most of which were energy use categories. As shown above, this highlights the fact that, although there was a net reduction in orchard-level GHG emissions due to the addition of mulch to the orchard, these emissions were outweighed by the mulch production impacts, and had a relatively small impact compared to the upstream impacts of other orchard inputs, most importantly fertilizer production.</ce:para>
                     <ce:section id="sec3.1.1" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.1.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0145">Sensitivity analysis</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0360" view="all">In the impact assessment above, a rate of 9.7% of C added from mulch was assumed to be sequestered long-term based on the methods for integration of soil C into life cycle assessment in <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0410" refid="bib23">Petersen et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref>. However, the biophysical interactions involved in soil C sequestration are dependent on many factors, therefore a sensitivity analysis was performed to determine the change in results if this assumed C sequestration rate were halved or doubled. Regardless of C sequestration rate (4.85%, 9.7% or 19.4%), the impacts of the mulch systems were higher than the clean systems (29%, 23%, and 7%, respectively) (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0415" refid="fig8">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>). The overall changes to life cycle GHG emissions were relatively small, but not negligible. When C sequestration rate was assumed to be 4.85%, the life cycle GHG emissions were 8% higher for the mulch systems compared to a C sequestration rate of 9.7%. At 19.4%, GHG emissions were 17% lower. The GHG emissions of the clean systems were the same for all assumed C sequestration rates because there was no C sequestration modelled in these treatments. This is because the C sequestration modelled in the mulched treatments is meant to represent the difference in C sequestration between mulched and non-mulched treatments (not the total amount of sequestration).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec3.1.2" view="all">
                        <ce:label>3.1.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sectitle0150">Uncertainty analysis</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0365" view="all">When only parameter uncertainty was accounted for in a Monte Carlo simulation, most impact category results were significantly higher for mulched systems than non-mulched. There were no significant differences in the depletion of abiotic resources between mulch and clean treatments, as well as eutrophication and primary forest energy use between mulch, low nitrogen and clean, low nitrogen. In all other impact categories, impacts for apple production with mulch were significantly higher than without mulch (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0420" refid="appsec1">Table S8</ce:cross-ref>). The impacts of the high nitrogen treatments were significantly higher for acidification, climate change, depletion of abiotic resources, photochemical oxidation, terrestrial ecotoxicity, land use (non-mulched treatments only), fossil energy use (non-mulched treatments only), nuclear energy use (mulched treatments only), geothermal energy use (non-mulched treatments only) and wind energy use (non-mulched treatments only). All other impact categories had no significant differences between low and high nitrogen treatments.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0370" view="all">The uncertainty of the results (measured as the standard deviation) greatly increased (up to 10<ce:sup loc="post">8</ce:sup> times higher), when both parameter and impact assessment uncertainty were included in the Monte Carlo simulation (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0425" refid="appsec1">Table S9</ce:cross-ref>). This was particularly true for the toxicity categories, since these impact categories have high levels of uncertainty in the characterization models used for impact assessment (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0430" refid="bib10">Huijbregts et al. (2003)</ce:cross-ref>). Due to this increased uncertainty, the impacts of the different apple production treatments for freshwater aquatic ecotoxicity, human toxicity, marine aquatic ecotoxicity and terrestrial ecotoxicity were no longer significantly different (for the effects of either nitrogen or mulch). The differences between low and high nitrogen treatments were also no longer significant for photochemical oxidation.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0375" view="all">Since it was not possible in the openLCA software to determine the relative contributions of each source of uncertainty in one Monte Carlo simulation, multiple Monte Carlo’s were performed. To approximate these relative contributions, the standard deviation of the Monte Carlo simulations with only background or foreground uncertainty were compared to the standard deviations of the Monte Carlo simulations with all parameter uncertainty included. Since these simulations were all independent, the amounts of uncertainty in each impact category were variable. Due to the high amount of uncertainty from both the background and foreground data, sometimes the standard deviation for certain impact categories was higher in the Monte Carlo simulation with only background or foreground uncertainty than in the simulation with all parameter uncertainty. Therefore this approximation of an uncertainty contribution analysis can give an indication of which sources of uncertainty may have been the most important contributors to the overall uncertainty, but it is not a robust assessment.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0380" view="all">Background uncertainty was 5–1564% of total parameter uncertainty, averaging 102% (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0435" refid="appsec1">Table S10</ce:cross-ref>). Foreground uncertainty was 4–106% of parameter uncertainty, averaging 57% (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0440" refid="appsec1">Table S11</ce:cross-ref>). These results indicate that a large amount of uncertainty came from both foreground and background data uncertainty, but background uncertainty accounted for a larger share of total uncertainty than foreground uncertainty. Background parameter uncertainty in this model came from data quality indicators – both those provided in the ecoinvent v.3.4 APOS processes used, as well as those modified according to the representativeness of these ecoinvent processes in the current application context. The data quality for these processes could be improved by the improved availability of temporally, geographically and technologically representative LCI datasets, specifically for the Canadian agri-food sector in the case of this model.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0385" view="all">In general, foreground parameter uncertainty for emissions-based impact categories was higher in high nitrogen treatments than low nitrogen treatments, with the standard deviation ranging up to 192% higher (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0445" refid="appsec1">Table S11</ce:cross-ref>). This was in part due to the differences in measured N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions, and higher variability in emissions when more nitrogen fertilizer was applied. This uncertainty in orchard-level emissions accounted for &lt;0.001–208% of the total foreground parameter uncertainty for emissions categories, averaging 26%. With only the uncertainty in orchard-level emissions accounted for, the high nitrogen treatment standard deviations ranged from 6% of to 9.06 × 10<ce:sup loc="post">4</ce:sup> times higher than low nitrogen (ESM – <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0450" refid="appsec1">STable 12</ce:cross-ref>). For resource use-based impact categories, the foreground uncertainty was similar between nitrogen treatments, but the mulch treatments had higher uncertainty than the clean treatments (up to 3.5 × 10<ce:sup loc="post">5</ce:sup> times higher) (ESM – <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0455" refid="appsec1">Table S11</ce:cross-ref>). This can be explained by the fact that mulch use contributed to the majority of land and energy use impacts. The uncertainty from mulch processes was 0.05–10294% of foreground parameter uncertainty, averaging 297% (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0460" refid="appsec1">Table S13</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0390" view="all">Since there are many sources of uncertainty that are common to each LCA scenario, the absolute amount of uncertainty is high in each scenario. However, since the aim of this study was to compare the difference in impacts of the different scenarios, the uncertainty common to each scenario is much less important than the uncertainty that is specific to the differences between treatments (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0465" refid="bib9">Henriksson et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). The impact assessment results with only the uncertainty that was not common between treatments had much lower uncertainty, averaging 9% of the total uncertainty (ESM - <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0470" refid="appsec1">Table S14</ce:cross-ref>). Due to this lower uncertainty, all differences between mulch treatments were significant except for primary forest energy use (low nitrogen treatments only). Most differences between nitrogen treatments were significant except for freshwater ecotoxicity (mulched treatments only), human toxicity (non-mulched treatments only), terrestrial ecotoxicity (non-mulched treatments only), land use (mulched treatments only), primary forest energy use (mulched treatments only), biomass energy use (mulched treatments only), geothermal energy use (mulched treatments only), solar energy use (mulched treatments only), water energy use (mulched treatments only) and wind energy use (mulched treatments only).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0155">Interpretation - limitations</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0395" view="all">Most relevant data for the construction and interpretation of this LCA model were available and complete (either from direct measurement or from existing LCI datasets); however, some important data were estimated using models due to a lack of data availability. These included the amount of soil C sequestered long-term, the orchard-level emissions due to plant protection and fertilizer application, and the inputs of some specific fertilizer and plant protection products. Exact LCI datasets for the input of most plant protection products (Kumulus, myclobutanil, Simazine, spirotetramat, DiPel, Diazinon, dormant oil and calcium) were not found, so generic LCI models for “insecticide” or “fungicide”, or alternative inputs similar to the actual product were used. This approximation was sufficient for this LCA model since, according to the goal and scope of the study, the aim was to determine the difference in environmental impacts between apples produced with mulch and without mulch. Since the fertilizer and plant production inputs were not the main focus of the study, and were the same between mulch and clean treatments, using non-specific data was sufficient to support the goal of the study. This is true for both the generic product inputs and upstream processes, as well as modelled emissions. The increase in SOC assumed to be sequestered, and thus removed from the atmosphere in the form of CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>, did contribute significantly (up to 17%) to the overall life cycle impacts, therefore a sensitivity analysis was conducted to determine the sensitivity of the results to the choice of the amount of C sequestered. The absolute amount of life cycle CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> emissions varied by up to 8% higher or 17% lower when the amount of C sequestered was varied from half the assumed value to double. However, the relative ranking of the treatments remained the same in all cases: apples produced with mulch produced more life cycle GHG emissions than without mulch. Since soil C sequestration contributed significantly to the results, improved accuracy of soil C sequestration modelling would be beneficial. This is an area for continued development in LCA methodology.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0400" view="all">Some data used in this LCA, while directly measured and relevant to the field-level experiments carried out at the SuRDC experimental plot, were not necessarily representative of orchards in the region. The amount of irrigation, fertilizer and herbicides applied to the orchard plots were the same regardless of mulch application, due to the experimental design. However, mulch application could improve water retention and reduce weeds (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0475" refid="bib20">Neilsen et al., 2003a</ce:cross-ref>), which could reduce the need for water and herbicide inputs. Therefore it would be necessary to design an experiment that took these changes in inputs into account and use those experimental results in an LCA study in order to model more representative impacts of adding mulch to apple orchards. Irrigation inputs have been shown to decrease by around 10% with the application of organic mulch such as straw and paper (<ce:cross-refs id="optzvn8rlOv8U" refid="bib36 bib35">Neilsen et al., 2017; Yin et al., 2012</ce:cross-refs>). Straw mulch was also shown to be even more effective than glyphosate at suppressing weed growth (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0480" refid="bib3">DeVetter et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>), indicating that herbicide use could be completely eliminated from mulched plots. These reductions in inputs would directly decrease the impacts associated with the application of these products and the upstream processes associated with their production and transportation. In addition, these reductions in inputs would influence orchard-level emissions. If herbicide application was eliminated, all herbicide emissions (both on the orchard, and upstream) would be eliminated. Decreasing water application could indirectly affect orchard-level emissions. Reduced irrigation was shown to decrease CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> emissions (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0485" refid="bib33">Zornoza et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) and N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0490" refid="bib34">Zornoza et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). However these studies did not account for the interaction of reduced irrigation and added mulch application, which could have different impacts on emissions. Increased soil moisture is associated with higher CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> and N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions due to higher microbial breakdown of soil organic matter, and increased denitrification (<ce:cross-ref id="crosref0495" refid="bib34">Zornoza et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>), therefore increased moisture retention due to mulch may also increase CO<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> and N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions. Given the complexity of these soil and emissions interactions, it would be misleading to construct LCA scenarios around reduced agro-chemical and water inputs, without emissions measurements similar to those in the <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0500" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> experiments. In order to study the life cycle impacts of mulch use in terms of water and herbicide use on Okanagan apple orchards, experiments would first need to be carried out to determine, in that climate, how much water and herbicide application could be reduced with the application of mulch. Then, similar experiments to <ce:cross-ref id="crosref0505" refid="bib4">Fentabil et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> would need to be carried out to determine the relative emissions and soil nutrient levels of mulched and non-mulched systems, including the different inputs of water and herbicides. These input and output data could then be included in a similar LCA model to this study in order to determine the net life cycle impacts of mulch application.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0160">Conclusions and recommendations</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0405" view="all">The life cycle GHG emissions of apple production using mulch as a soil amendment were 25% higher than without mulch, despite the observed reduction in orchard-level N<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O emissions and increase SOC. This is because the upstream GHG emissions associated with the production, transportation and application of the mulch outweighed those benefits. In fact, all life cycle impacts for emissions-based impact categories were 13–50% higher for apple production using mulch because the production of the mulch increased upstream emissions without an equal reduction of emissions anywhere in the life cycle. Resource use was even higher (80–99% higher for mulched treatments compared to non-mulched) due to the land and energy needed to create the mulch as a co-product of lumber production. Instead of considering mulch a burden-free by-product, all emissions and resource use were allocated on a mass ratio basis to both the lumber and mulch products produced at the sawmill. However, mulch production impacts were not the main contributor to most life cycle emissions impact categories. These were dominated by fertilizer production, transportation, application, and modelled emissions of ammonia, nitrate, nitrogen oxides and phosphorus, which were the same in both the mulch and no mulch scenarios, and accounted for the largest share of impacts in 7 out of 9 emissions impact categories. For resource use impact categories, however, mulch production was the highest contributor for 7 out of 10 categories.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0410" view="all">Long-term soil C sequestration is a proposed benefit of mulch, and was modelled based on the amount of C added to the system in the mulched treatments. This model assumption was examined using a sensitivity analysis to vary the assumed amount of C sequestered by 100% (halving and doubling the amount). This altered the life cycle GHG emissions by 8–17%, but in all cases the mulch systems were still 7–29% higher than clean. There was a high amount of uncertainty in this LCA model, from stochastic variability of measured data, data quality, methodological choices, and impact assessment methods. However, most of these sources of uncertainty were common between all apple production treatments. When only considering the foreground parameter uncertainty that was unique to each treatment, almost all differences between treatments were statistically significant, meaning that impacts were higher for mulched compared to non-mulched treatments.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0415" view="all">Taken together, these results suggest that the increased resource use and associated emissions necessary for the production, transportation and application of mulch outweigh the measured reductions in GHG emissions with mulch application compared to no mulch. These results assumed that all other orchard inputs remained the same, based on the previous experimental design. However the other potential orchard-level benefits that may be associated with the use of bark mulch, such as nutrient and water retention, increase in soil organic matter and the many associated benefits, and suppression of weeds were not accounted for in this study. These benefits could outweigh the increased impacts seen in this study, for overall beneficial sustainability impacts of mulch use on orchards. Future research should focus on the collection of data for water use, herbicide use and soil nutrients associated with the use of mulch, and inclusion of these data into life cycle modelling.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec5" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0165">Funding</ce:section-title>
